            "abstractNote": "Monitoring of macroinvertebrate communities is frequently used to deﬁne the ecological health status of rivers. Ideally, biomonitoring should also give an indication on the major stressors acting on the macroinvertebrate communities supporting the selection of appropriate management measures. However, most indices are affected by more than one stressor. Biological traits (e.g. size, generation time, reproduction) could potentially lead to more stressor-speciﬁc indices. However, such an approach has rarely been tested.",
